        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Based on single dish measurements, the linewidth of the integrated CO emission corresponds to 200 km/s (FWHM: Baan+08). Thus, the overall velocity field is well sampled with an effective velocity resolution of 20 km/s, that drives the requested rms value. Moreover, the outflowing/inflowing  velocities have a peak to peak value of 200 km/s, and therefore the expected outflowing molecular gas will also be resolved. Finally, the spectral resolution of 5 km/s requested in the spectral setup will allow to determine (although with a lower S/N ratio) the shape of the line profile and any other velocity susbstructure.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request to observe the CO(201) line with a resolution of 0.2 arcsec, i.e. using the C36-5 configuration. At the distance of the galaxy, this angular resolution corresponds to about 20 pc, enough to map the region of 300 pc where the inflows and outflows are observed (Riffel+09). The maximum recoverable scale for the C36-5 configuration corresponds to 3.4 arcsec that is adequate to map the circumnuclear star-forming ring structure.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>NGC7582 has total CO (1-0) flux of 696 Jy km/s (Baan+08, A&amp;A, 477,747) within 34 arcsec. Assuming a 1D spatial dilution factor (conservative limit for galaxies if the velocity structure due to the rotation field and the low filling factor of the emission are both taken into account), and a CO(2-1) to CO(1-0) ratio of one, we expect ~4 Jy km/s/beam for a beam of 0.2 arcsec. The CO(1-0) line profile has a FWHM of 200 km/s (Baan+08), and therefore the expected peak flux corresponds to 20mJy/beam. Considering the outflow component containing about 10-20% of the total flux, we would expect a flux of 2-4 mJy/beam in the outflow. In order to detect this component at significant levels (i.e., 5 to 10 sigma), a rms of 0.4 mJy is required for a velocity resolution of 20 km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
