    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA CO (2-1) observations of the inner 300 pc of the nearby Seyfert 2 galaxy NGC7582 to obtain the cold molecular gas mass distribution and kinematics. This galaxy can be considered a prototype of its class as our near-IR integral field observations of the gas kinematics revealed all nuclear characteristics we have been finding in our study of a complete sample of nearby Seyfert galaxies: a rotating disk of hot (2000K) H2 extending out to a star-forming ring at 200 pc from the nucleus, inflows in hot H2 along a nuclear bar, and outflows along its [OIII] ionization cone. As the nuclear bar is oriented close to the ionization cone, the hot H2 kinematics could also be solely due to outflows along the ionization cone. We propose to use ALMA in the C36-5 configuration (~20 pc spatial resolution) to map the expected much more massive nuclear flows in cold molecular gas and answer the following questions: (1) What is the dominant cold H2 kinematics: inflow or outflow? (2) Which are the total masses and mass flow rates? (3) Which is the geometry of the outflow? (4) Which is its velocity and power? Can it quench the circumnuclear star formation?</prp:abstract>
